SIMPLE: stanch
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stanch
<hw>Stanch</hw> <pr>(st⟦adot⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stanched</conjf>
<pr>(st⟦adot⟧ncht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stanching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>estanchier</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tancher</ets> to stop a liquid from flowing; akin to Pr.,
Sp., & Pg. <ets>estancar</ets>, It. <ets>stancare</ets> to weary, LL.
<ets>stancare</ets>, <ets>stagnare</ets>, to stanch, fr. L.
<ets>stagnare</ets> to be or make stagnant. See
<er>Stagnate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To stop the flowing of, as
blood; to check; also, to stop the flowing of blood from; <as>as, to
<ex>stanch</ex> a wound</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>staunch</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Iron or a stone laid to the neck doth <qex>stanch</qex> the
bleeding of the nose.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To extinguish; to quench, as fire or thirst.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stanch
<hw>Stanch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cease, as the flowing of
blood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Immediately her issue of blood <qex>stanched</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke viii. 44.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stanch
<hw>Stanch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which stanches or
checks.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A flood gate by which water is accumulated, for
floating a boat over a shallow part of a stream by its release.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stanch
<hw>Stanch</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Stancher</adjf> <pr>(-⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Stanchest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[From <er>Stanch</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>, and hence literally signifying, stopped or stayed; cf. Sp.
<ets>estanco</ets> stopped, tight, not leaky, as a ship. See
<er>Stanch</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>staunch</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Strong and tight; sound;
firm; <as>as, a <ex>stanch</ex> ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of the closets is parqueted with plain deal, set in diamond,
exceeding <qex>stanch</qex> and pretty.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Firm in principle; constant and zealous; loyal;
hearty; steady; steadfast; <as>as, a <ex>stanch</ex> churchman; a
<ex>stanch</ex> friend or adherent</as>.</def> <rj><au>V.
Knox.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In politics I hear you 're <qex>stanch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Close; secret; private.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is to be kept <qex>stanch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Stanch
<hw>Stanch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To prop; to make stanch, or
strong.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His gathered sticks to <qex>stanch</qex> the wall⟦br⟧
Of the snow tower when snow should fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stanchel</ent>⟦br⟧
